description.explanation: The C#7-5 (or C#7b5) alter the C#7 by the change of one note. C#7-5 stands for C sharp seven minus five.
description.theory:
The C#7-5 are identical with the C#7 except that the fifth tone of the scale (i.e. the third tone in the chord) is flattened
.
description.fingerings: Little finger, middle finger, index finger, thumb (left hand); thumb, index finger, middle finger, little finger (right hand).

description.explanation: The C#sus4 and C#sus2 are three-note chords. A#sus2 is sometimes written as C#2.
description.theory:
In these chords, the third (the second note in the chord) are being replaced with either a major second
or a perfect four
. The sus4 chord includes a perfect four and the sus2 chord includes a major second.

description.explanation: The Db7-5 (or Db7b5) alter the Db7 by the change of one note. Db7-5 stands for D flat seven minus five.
description.theory:
The Db7-5 are identical with the Db7 except that the fifth tone of the scale (i.e. the third tone in the chord) is flattened
.
description.fingerings: Little finger, middle finger, index finger, thumb (left hand); thumb, index finger, middle finger, little finger (right hand).

description.explanation: The D7-5 (or D7b5) alter the D7 by the change of one note. D7-5 stands for D seven minus five.
description.theory:

.

description.explanation: The D#7-5 (or D#7b5) alter the D#7 by the change of one note. D#7-5 stands for D sharp seven plus five.
description.theory:
The D#7-5 are identical with the D#7 except that the fifth tone of the scale (i.e. the third tone in the chord) is flattened
.
description.fingerings: Little finger, middle finger, index finger, thumb (left hand); thumb, index finger, middle finger, little finger (right hand).

.

description.explanation: The F#7-5 (or F#7b5) alter the F#7 by the change of one note. F#7-5 stands for F sharp seven minus five.
description.theory:
The F#7-5 are identical with the F#7 except that the fifth tone of the scale (i.e. the third tone in the chord) is flattened
.

description.explanation: The F#sus4 and F#sus2 are three-note chords. F#sus2 is sometimes written as F#2.
description.theory:
In these chords, the third (the second note in the chord) are being replaced with either a major second
or a perfect four
. The sus4 chord includes a perfect four and the sus2 chord includes a major second.

description.explanation: The Gb7-5 (or Gb7b5) alter the Gb7 by the change of one note. Gb7-5 stands for G flat seven minus five.

description.explanation: The G7-5 (or G7b5) alter the G7 by the change of one note. G7-5 stands for G seven minus five.
description.theory:
The G7-5 are identical with the G7 except that the fifth tone of the scale (i.e. the third tone in the chord) is flattened
.
description.fingerings: Little finger, middle finger, index finger, thumb (left hand); thumb, index finger, middle finger, little finger (right hand).

description.explanation: The Gsus4 and Gsus2 are three-note chords. Gsus2 is sometimes written as G2.
description.theory:

or a perfect four
. The sus4 chord includes a perfect four and the sus2 chord includes a major second.

description.explanation: The G#7-5 (or G#7b5) alter the G#7 by the change of one note. G#7-5 stands for G sharp seven minus five.
description.theory:
The G#7-5 are identical with the G#7 except that the fifth tone of the scale (i.e. the third tone in the chord) is flattened
.
description.fingerings: Little finger, middle finger, index finger, thumb (left hand); thumb, index finger, middle finger, little finger (right hand).

description.explanation: The Ab7-5 (or Ab7b5) alter the Ab7 by the change of one note. Ab7-5 stands for A flat seven minus five.
description.theory:
The Ab7-5 are identical with the Ab7 except that the fifth tone of the scale (i.e. the third tone in the chord) is flattened
.

THEORY:The A# minor eleventh chord is constructed by adding a third to a minor ninth chord.

description.explanation: The A#add9 and A#add2 are four-note chords. A#add2 is sometimes written as A#2.
description.theory: Both chords contain the same notes, but the added notes belong to different octaves which are the ninth and the second notes in the scale.

description.explanation: The A#7-5 (or A#7b5) alter the A#7 by the change of one note. A#7-5 stands for A sharp seven minus five.
description.theory:
The A#7-5 are identical with the A#7 except that the fifth tone of the scale (i.e. the third tone in the chord) is flattened
.
description.fingerings: Little finger, middle finger, index finger, thumb (left hand); thumb, index finger, middle finger, little finger (right hand).

.

description.explanation: The B7-5 (or B7b5) alter the B7 by the change of one note. B7-5 stands for B seven minus five.
description.theory:
The B7-5 are identical with the B7 except that the fifth tone of the scale (i.e. the third tone in the chord) is flattened
.
description.fingerings: Little finger, middle finger, index finger, thumb (left hand); thumb, index finger, middle finger, little finger (right hand).

description.explanation: The Bsus4 and Bsus2 are three-note chords. Bsus2 is sometimes written as B2.
description.theory:
In these chords, the third (the second note in the chord) are being replaced with either a major second
or a perfect four
. The sus4 chord includes a perfect four and the sus2 chord includes a major second.
